   <text>
      <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-06_page01.jpg"/>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg"/>
            <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <name type="place" ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE">Edgeworths Town</name><lb/>
                  <date when="1829-06-07"/>June 7, 1829. </dateline>
               <salute>
                  My dear Sir
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p><!-- Begin transcibing the body of the letter here. -->
            </p>
            <p>
                  The chance of this finding<lb/>
                  you in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">Town</placeName> is small - but<lb/>
                  <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FrenX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. French</persName> will broach this to<lb/>
                  you wherever you are &amp; as<lb/>
                  this <unclear>probable</unclear> you may not have<lb/>
                  time to give us the pleasure<lb/>
                  of seeing you (<unclear>as</unclear> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. <unclear>Jameson</unclear><lb/>
                  you wish never <unclear></unclear> as we do)<lb/>
                  in your way home I am <choice><orig>anxi<lb/>
                  ous</orig><reg>anxious</reg></choice> to get a speedy answer<lb/>
                  to this question<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>Is there any consul or vice<lb/>
                  consulship that you know<lb/>
                  of vacant in any part of the<lb/>
                  world that you would like to<lb/>
                  go to or any manner of a<lb/>
                  place or employment abroad<lb/>
                  that w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> suit your <hi rend="underline">health</hi><lb/>
                  taste &amp; finances &amp; make<lb/>
                  it worth your while to give<lb/>
                  up <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Loughglynn_IE">Loughglynn</placeName> &amp; to leave<lb/>
                  or take certain of your family<lb/>
                  <add>&amp; have <unclear>others</unclear> at school or with friends</add><lb/>
                  with you - Think of it &amp;<lb/>
                  answer me in person if<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-06_page02.jpg"/>

                  you can because we could<lb/>
                  talk over &amp; <unclear>I</unclear> understand<lb/>
                  best <hi rend="underline">so</hi> - But if you cannot<lb/>
                  come <hi rend="underline">write</hi>.<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>I have another that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MurrG1">Sir G<lb/>
                  Murray</persName> <unclear>knows</unclear> you - knew<lb/>
                  you in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IN">India</placeName> - If so pray<lb/>
                  see him if you can &amp; just<lb/>
                  revive &amp; leave an impression<lb/>
                  of yourself upon his mind -<lb/>
               </p>
               <p><persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> has made me<lb/>
                  by her last letter more anxious<lb/>
                  even than I was before that<lb/>
                  your <unclear></unclear> should not<lb/>
                  be painfully doomed to<lb/>
                  <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Loughglynn_IE">Lougha Glynn</placeName> - I have but<lb/>
                  one scheme &amp; one chance<lb/>
                  which you perhaps will<lb/>
                  think not worth the <unclear>trying</unclear><lb/>
                  - But boldness <del>(</del> I (being a<lb/>
                  woman) have found the best<lb/>
                  thing in doing business, I mean<lb/>
                  in asking favors from the<lb/>
                  great (Please not to mention it)<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-06_page03.jpg"/>

                  even to your own self - <unclear>your</unclear><lb/>
                  <unclear>sober</unclear> rational self if you<lb/>
                  can help it -) But my <choice><orig>in-<lb/>
                  tention</orig><reg>intention</reg></choice> is to write straight<lb/>
                  to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WellA1">Duke of Wellington</persName> &amp;<lb/>
                  ask him for what you <choice><orig>wd</orig><reg>would</reg></choice><lb/>
                  like if you can shape out<lb/>
                  in any feasible form what<lb/>
                  we could ask -<lb/>
               </p>
               <p>Do not <hi rend="underline">pray</hi> mention<lb/>
                  this to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> because she<lb/>
                  would tremble for my<lb/>
                  temerity.<lb/>
               </p>
            <closer>
               Ever yours truly<lb/>
               <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
            </closer>
            <postscript>
               <p>
               I know that a new Brazilian<lb/>
               company <del><unclear></unclear></del> offered <del><unclear>Lord?</unclear></del><lb/>
               lately through <add><unclear>?A S W <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OgleX1">Ogle</persName> to??</unclear></add> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">my brother<lb/>
               Sneyd</persName> to give <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">my poor<lb/>
               brother William</persName> 2000 <hi rend="superscript">£</hi> per,<lb/>
               <choice><orig>Ann<hi rend="superscript">m</hi></orig><reg>Annum</reg></choice>. salary <add>&amp; a fine house</add> if he would be<lb/>
               their Engineer - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeC1">Sneyd</persName> was<lb/>
            <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Princeton_1829-06_page04.jpg"/>

               told this a few days ago by <persName ref="./Personography.xml#OgleX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ogle</persName><lb/>
               who did not know that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeW1">poor<lb/>
               William</persName> was gone from this world.<lb/>
               </p>
            </postscript>
            <closer><!--Use the <closer> element again to hold Address Leaf information.-->
               <address>
                  <addrLine>J. E. Strickland Esq<hi rend="superscript">er</hi><lb/>
                  </addrLine>
               </address>
            </closer>
         </div>
